{
  "local_port": 56916,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How can I get YouTube comments?",
  "response": "To get YouTube comments programmatically, we need to use the YouTube Data API. Here's a step-by-step approach to retrieve comments for a specific video using Python:\n\n1. First, we need to set up a project in Google Cloud Console and enable the YouTube Data API.\n2. We'll need to create credentials for the API (OAuth 2.0 client ID for a desktop application).\n3. We'll use the `google-api-python-client` library to interact with the API.\n\nLet's write a Python script to fetch comments:\n\n```python\nfrom google.oauth2.credentials import Credentials\nfrom googleapiclient.discovery import build\nimport google_auth_oauthlib.flow\n\n# Replace these with your actual client ID and secret\nCLIENT_ID = 'YOUR_CLIENT_ID'\nCLIENT_SECRET = 'YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET'\n\n# Video ID for which we want to get comments\nVIDEO_ID = 'dQw4w9WgXcQ'  # Example: Rick Astley - Never Gonna Give You Up\n\n# Number of comments to retrieve\nMAX_RESULTS = 50\n\ndef authenticate():\n    \"\"\"\n    Authenticate with Google and return the YouTube API client\n    \"\"\"\n    # The file token.json stores the user's access and refresh tokens, and is\n    # created automatically when the authorization flow completes for the first\n    # time.\n    token_file = 'token.json'\n    \n    creds = None\n    if creds and creds.expired and creds.refresh_token:\n        creds.refresh(Request())\n    else:\n        flow = google_auth_oauthlib.flow.InstalledAppFlow.from_client_secrets_file(\n            'client_secrets.json', ['https://www.googleapis.com/auth/youtube.force-ssl'])\n        creds = flow.run_local_server(port=0)\n        \n        # Save the credentials for the next run\n        with open(token_file, 'w') as token:\n            token.write(creds.to_json())\n\n    return build('youtube', 'v3', credentials=creds)\n\ndef get_comments(youtube, video_id, max_results):\n    \"\"\"\n    Retrieve comments for a given video ID\n    \"\"\"\n    comments = []\n    \n    request = youtube.commentThreads().list(\n        part=\"snippet\",\n        videoId=video_id,\n        maxResults=max_results\n    )\n    \n    while request:\n        response = request.execute()\n        \n        for item in response['items']:\n            comment = item['snippet']['topLevelComment']['snippet']\n            comments.append({\n                'author': comment['authorDisplayName'],\n                'text': comment['textDisplay'],\n                'published_at': comment['publishedAt']\n            })\n        \n        request = youtube.commentThreads().list_next(request, response)\n    \n    return comments\n\ndef main():\n    # Authenticate and create the YouTube API client\n    youtube = authenticate()\n    \n    # Get comments for the specified video\n    comments = get_comments(youtube, VIDEO_ID, MAX_RESULTS)\n    \n    # Print the comments\n    for comment in comments:\n        print(f\"Author: {comment['author']}\")\n        print(f\"Comment: {comment['text']}\")\n        print(f\"Published at: {comment['published_at']}\")\n        print(\"---\")\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    main()\n```\n\nTo use this script:\n\n1. Install the required libraries:\n   ```\n   pip install google-api-python-client google-auth-httplib2 google-auth-oauthlib\n   ```\n\n2. Create a file named `client_secrets.json` in the same directory as the script with your client ID and secret:\n   ```json\n   {\n     \"installed\": {\n       \"client_id\": \"YOUR_CLIENT_ID\",\n       \"project_id\": \"YOUR_PROJECT_ID\",\n       \"auth_uri\": \"https://accounts.google.com/o/oauth2/auth\",\n       \"token_uri\": \"https://oauth2.googleapis.com/token\",\n       \"auth_provider_x509_cert_url\": \"https://www.googleapis.com/oauth2/v1/certs\",\n       \"client_secret\": \"YOUR_CLIENT_SECRET\",\n       \"redirect_uris\": [\"urn:ietf:wg:oauth:2.0:oob\", \"http://localhost\"]\n     }\n   }\n   ```\n\n3. Run the script. It will open a browser window for you to authenticate with Google. After authentication, it will fetch and display the comments.\n\nNote that this script retrieves top-level comments only. If you need replies to comments, you'll need to modify the script to fetch them separately using the `comments()` method of the YouTube API.\n\nAlso, be aware of the API usage limits and ensure you comply with YouTube's terms of service when using this data.",
